# LangGraph Design Notes

This document captures key architectural decisions for building multi-agent
systems with LangGraph, intended as sample content for the project's local
knowledge base.

## Supervisor-Worker Pattern

LangGraph's StateGraph makes it natural to implement a supervisor-worker
topology: a central supervisor node inspects the shared state and emits a
`Command(goto=...)` to route execution to one of several worker nodes. Each
worker updates the state and returns control to the supervisor, which decides
the next step. This pattern works better than a fixed pipeline when the number
of steps is unknown a priori (e.g., "search until enough sources are gathered").

## Checkpointing

The graph is compiled with a checkpointer (PostgreSQL in production,
MemorySaver as a fallback). Checkpointing means a run can be paused and
resumed across process restarts, which is essential for long-running research
tasks and for Human-in-the-Loop flows that wait on user input.

## Streaming Events

`graph.astream_events(version="v2")` yields granular `on_chain_start` /
`on_chain_end` / `on_tool_start` / `on_tool_end` events that a UI can map to
human-readable status messages, giving end users real-time visibility into
which agent is active and what tools it is calling.

## Interrupt for Human-in-the-Loop

Calling `interrupt(value)` inside a node suspends the graph and surfaces
`value` to the caller. Resuming with `Command(resume=...)` injects the user's
response back into the node, enabling approval gates, plan editing, and
rejection paths without re-running earlier work.